'''Kyoto Hemp Forum''' (also called 世界麻環境フォーラム京都, International Hemp Environmental Forum Kyoto) is a [[hemp]] industry event held in Kyoto. The first event was held in July 2016.<ref>{{citation|newspaper=[[Japan Times]]|title=Views from Kyoto: What does the future hold for hemp in Japan? – Attendees at the International Hemp Forum, which was held at the Kyoto International Convention Center earlier this month, speak about their hopes for hemp in Japan.|author=John Ashburne|date=July 13, 2016|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/community/2016/07/13/voices/views-kyoto-future-hold-hemp-japan/}}</ref> Featured speakers included Japanese politicians first lady [[Akie Abe]] and the Mayor of Kyoto, [[Daisaku Kadokawa]], as well as U.S. activist [[Chris Conrad (author)|Chris Conrad]] and Dutch seed enterpreneur [[Sensi Seeds|Ben Dronkers]].<ref>{{citation|title=Japanese First Lady to Headline Inaugural Kyoto Hemp Forum|work=Hemp Today|date=June 9, 2016|url=https://hemptoday.net/first-lady-kyoto-hemp-forum/}}</ref><ref>{{citation|publisher=Sensi Seeds|title=Ben Dronkers at Kyoto Hemp Forum 2016|date=July 1, 2016|url=https://sensiseeds.com/en/blog/ben-dronkers-kyoto-hemp-forum-2016/}}</ref> The title of Conrad's book ''Hemp: Lifeline to the Future'' was also the official theme of the event.<ref>{{citation|first=Chris|last=Conrad|title=Kyoto Hemp Forum, July 2016–Hemp: Lifeline to the Future|work=official blog|date=May 26, 2016|url=http://chrisconrad.com/2016/05/kyoto-hemp-forum-july-2016/}}</ref> Exhibitors at the forum include an Australian hemp seed company whose biggest market is Japan.<ref>{{citation|title=Hemp food producer expecting 400 per cent growth in next 12 months|work=ABC Rural|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|author=Kim Honan |date=18 July 2016|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/rural/2016-07-19/hemp-food-export-growth/7640076}}</ref>

